<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-039-092 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 408 887</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  Oct 7 1991 n662 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Canon fires off the first viable ferro-LCD screen. (ferroelectricliquid crystal displays)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kaplan, Doug; Lieberman, David.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Canon Inc will demonstrate the first practical ferroelectricliquid crystal displays (FLCD) at Japan's Data Show 1991 in Tokyo.andO;Canon's devices will consist of a 960- by 1,312-pixel, 15-inchmonochrome FLCD and prototypes of two 1,280- by 1,024-pixel,15-inch color FLCDs.andP;  One of the color FLCDs will use twosubpixels per pixel and the other will use four.andP;  Canon seniordirector Hiroshi Tanaka estimates that the new technology willallow Canon to acquire 50 percent of the computer display marketin Japan between 1991 and 1996.andP;  FLCDs offer improved speed,inherent memory characteristics, and optical quality over thecurrently popular LCD screens.andP;  FLCDs also offer benefits over CRTtechnology, since they generate a very low electromagnetic fieldand very little x-ray radiation.andP;  No US manufacturers are workingon FLCD projects, despite the fact that much of the Canontechnology is based on research done in the US.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Canon Inc. (Product development).andO;Topic:     Liquid Crystal DisplaysScreensColorMonochromeProduct DevelopmentNew TechniqueMarketing Strategy.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Out of the lab: ferroelectric LCD cell structure. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>